SIMPLE: heck
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Heck
<hw>Heck</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Hatch</er> a
half door.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>hack</asp>.]</altsp>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The bolt or latch of a door.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A rack for cattle to feed at.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A door, especially one partly of latticework; --
called also <altname>heck door</altname>.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A latticework contrivance for catching
fish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>An apparatus for separating the
threads of warps into sets, as they are wound upon the reel from the
bobbins, in a warping machine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A bend or winding of a stream.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Half heck</b></col>, <cd>the lower half of a door.</cd>
-- <col><b>Heck board</b></col>, <cd>the loose board at the bottom or
back of a cart.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Heck box</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>Heck frame</b></col></mcol>, <cd>that which carries the heck in
warping.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Heck
<hw>Heck</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>hell; -- a euphemism.
Used commonly in the phrase ⟦ldquo⟧What the
<xex>heck</xex>⟦rdquo⟧.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heckerism</ent>⟦br⟧
